Part I - Proster Loan Data¶

by Natalia Bobkova¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

This data dictionary explains the variables in the data set.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 cases of loan in the dataset with 81 features. Most variables are numeric (61), but the categorical variables are present as well.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I would like to know which borrower information is correlated to Prosper Score. In particular, the following properties might be interesting:

  1. ListingCategory (numeric)

The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans.

  1. EmploymentStatusDuration

The length in months of the employment status at the time the listing was created.

  1. EmploymentStatus

The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.

  1. ProsperScore

A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

  1. CurrentCreditLines

Number of current credit lines at the time the credit profile was pulled.

  1. IncomeVerifiable

The borrower indicated they have the required documentation to support their income.

  1. LoanOriginalAmount

The origination amount of the loan.

  1. LoanStatus

The current status of the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think Loan Original Amount should be highly correlated to Prosper Score. Information on Employment Status & Employment status duration may be of great impact as well. Finally, Loan Status might provide some information on Prosper Score as well.

Data Wrangling¶

ListingCategory is numeric, the values are not explicit, we will need to transform them to categorical data

In [7]:
# Transform ListingCategory (numeric) feature into categorical
list_dict = {0 : 'Not Available', 1 : 'Debt Consolidation', 2 : 'Home Improvement', 3: 'Business', 
             4 : 'Personal Loan', 5 : 'Student Use', 6 : 'Auto', 7 : 'Other', 8 : 'Baby&Adoption', 
             9 : 'Boat', 10 : 'Cosmetic Procedure', 11 : 'Engagement Ring', 12 : 'Green Loans',
             13 : 'Household Expenses', 14 : 'Large Purchases', 15 : 'Medical/Dental', 16 : 'Motorcycle',
             17 : 'RV', 18 : 'Taxes', 19 : 'Vacation', 20 : 'Wedding Loans'}

loan_data['ListingCategory (numeric)'] = loan_data['ListingCategory (numeric)'].replace(list_dict)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I had to perform data groupping in order to avoid variables with low representation (Past Due for Loan Status). I also dropped very infrequent data (Cancelled and Final Payment in Progress always for Loan Status).

The one result that stroke me most is the shape of Prosper Score distribution - it is more or less normal, whereas I would expect is to be skewed, either positively, or negatively. It means that borrowers tend to take moderate risk, few of them don't risk at all, neither put all in.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Other and Not Available Values are disturbing in Employment Status. For a moment I kept them as is, since the presence of these values does not change figure interpretations for exploratory data analysis. However, I will need to remove these data for explanatory analysis

In [ ]:

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

One correlation I found interesting here is between Prosper Score and Original Loan Amount. The higher is the amount, the higher the score. It means that lower risks are associated with higher loan amounts. At the same time, Prosper Score has the same distribution across different subgroups of Loan Status, whereas full-time employed people prefer low risk, and self-employed people prefer high risks.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I found it interesting and at the same time no surprising that Employment Status is correlated to Employment Status Duration. For example, not employed and part-time employed status both have the lowest duration, indeed, it may be considered as a transition status. On the contrary, self-employed, employed and full-time employed status have a longer duration.

Another interesting (and also non surprising discovery) was the correlation between Employment Status and the ability to prove this status: self-employed people have more problemns than other groups in providing such documentation.
